==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in 1380.
* From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|absence|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|absence|lang=fro}}, {{term|ausence|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|absentia|lang=la}}, from {{term|absens|absēns|absent|lang=la}}, present active participle of {{term|absum||I am away or absent|lang=la}}, from {{term|ab||from, away from|lang=la}} + {{term|sum||I am|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.səns/|/ˈæb.sənts/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"{bs@ns/|/"{bs@nts/}}
* {{audio|en-us-absence.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# A state of being absent or [[withdrawn]] from a place or from [[companionship]].
#* {{rfdate}} ''Phillippians 2:12''
#*: Not as in my presence only, but now much more in my '''absence'''.
# Failure to be present where one is expected, wanted, or needed; nonattendence; deficiency.
#* {{rfdate}} - [[Kent]]
#*: In the '''absence''' of conventional law.
#: He had an '''absence''' of enthusiasm.
# [[inattention|Inattention]] to things present; [[abstraction]] (of mind)
#: '''''absence''' of mind.''
#* {{rfdate}}, [[w:Joseph Addison|Joseph Addison]]
#*: Reflecting on the little '''absences''' and distractions of mankind.
#* {{rfdate}} - [[Landor]]
#*: To conquer that abstraction which is called '''absence'''.
# {{medical}} Temporary loss or disruption of consciousness, with sudden onset and recovery, and common in epilepsy.
# {{fencing}} Lack of contact between [[blade]]s.

